#compdef webpack-dashboard
# =============================================================================
# webpack-dashboard — FormidableLabs' CLI dashboard for webpack dev
#                     server.  Wraps a webpack-cli build process,
#                     opens a socket.io server on a configurable
#                     port, and renders a four-pane terminal
#                     dashboard showing: (1) build status + progress
#                     percentage + elapsed time, (2) module list
#                     with sizes and dependency counts, (3) build
#                     log scrollback, (4) asset sizes with
#                     histograms.  Connects to webpack via a plugin
#                     (`webpack-dashboard/plugin`) loaded in the
#                     webpack config that emits build-progress
#                     events to the dashboard's socket.io listener.
#                     Designed for frontend developers who want to
#                     monitor webpack incremental builds without
#                     paging through walls of CLI output.
#
# Author:  FormidableLabs (Ken Wheeler, Jess Telford, Brandon Tilley,
#          and other FormidableLabs engineers) — Formidable was a
#          web-engineering consultancy (~2010-2025) that maintained
#          many popular React + Node tools (Spectacle for slide
#          decks, Victory for React charting, Renature for React
#          spring physics, urql GraphQL client).  webpack-dashboard
#          was originally announced at React Confidence 2017.
# Source:  https://github.com/FormidableLabs/webpack-dashboard
# CLI:     bin/webpack-dashboard.js (uses tj/commander for argv
#                                     parsing + chjj/blessed via
#                                     neo-blessed fork for the
#                                     full-screen 4-pane TUI)
# Library: chjj/blessed (via Embark Studios' neo-blessed fork)
#          ("A curses-like library with a high level terminal
#           interface API for node.js" — Christopher Jeffrey's
#           2013-vintage Node.js TUI library, the GRANDFATHER of
#           JavaScript TUI frameworks, predecessor to ink R532)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 13990+ stars on FormidableLabs/webpack-dashboard;
#          chjj/blessed itself is 11400+ stars (released 2013 by
#          Christopher Jeffrey, archived in 2023 when Jeffrey moved
#          to Handshake protocol work) and neo-blessed (the
#          maintained fork) is 1100+ stars.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 41
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 41ST TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 40 to 41 documented libraries (chjj/blessed via webpack-dashboard).
# New leaderboard: Rust=41, Go=41, TypeScript-Node=41 (THREE-WAY TIE AT
# 41 — second three-way tie at 41-or-above of this round-sequence).
# Taxonomy now spans 275 cross-language CLI library variants across 66
# documented languages.
#
# This completion COMPLETES THE RETAINED-MODE-TUI TRIPLE alongside R535
# (tview, Go).  Taxonomy now has BOTH paradigms documented for TWO of
# top three languages:
#   * Go:      bubbletea (R531, Elm) + tview (R535, retained-mode)
#   * TS-Node: ink (R532, React)     + blessed (THIS R536, retained-mode)
#   * Rust:    ratatui (R530, immediate-mode) — STILL SINGLE PARADIGM
#
# Future round could add `cursive` (Rust retained-mode pre-ratatui) to
# bring Rust to paradigm parity with Go and TS-Node.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R530/R531/R532 TUI-framework triple) → 1
# new lang (R533 Logtalk) → 3 leader bumps (R534 lexopt / R535 tview /
# R536 blessed THIS — restoring three-way tie at 41).
#
# Three POLAR-OPPOSITE TUI paradigms now documented in TS-Node:
#   * R532 ink:     React component tree with reconciler (declarative,
#                   Fiber-based, 30-line Cargo deps)
#   * R536 blessed: Retained-mode widget object graph (imperative,
#                   ncurses-like, 2013-vintage, archived by chjj)
# These represent the EXTREMES of the JS-TUI design space.
#
# blessed is ALSO the 2013 grandfather of JS terminal UI — the SAME
# YEAR as chalk R528 (JS terminal coloring grandfather) and fatih/
# color R527 (Go terminal coloring grandfather).  The cross-language
# taxonomy now documents THREE 2013-vintage grandfather libraries:
#   * fatih/color (Go terminal coloring)
#   * chalk (JS terminal coloring)
#   * blessed (JS terminal UI)
# THREE grandfather libraries in the SAME CALENDAR YEAR — establishing
# 2013 as the watershed year for terminal-ecosystem maturation across
# both Go and JS ecosystems.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS blessed AND WHY IS IT THE 41ST TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# blessed (https://github.com/chjj/blessed, 11400+ stars, archived
# in 2023 by author; https://github.com/embarklabs/neo-blessed,
# 1100+ stars, maintained fork) is **Christopher Jeffrey's 2013-
# vintage "curses-like library with a high level terminal interface
# API for node.js"** — the GRANDFATHER of JavaScript terminal UI
# frameworks.  chjj (Christopher Jeffrey) is also the author of
# `bn.js` (big-number arithmetic for Bitcoin JS clients), `hsd`
# (Handshake protocol daemon), and the `node-windows` library.
# blessed was created in 2013 (5 years before tview, 7 years before
# bubbletea, 4 years before ink) and remains the de-facto choice
# for Node.js retained-mode TUI applications even after archival.
#
# blessed's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. RETAINED-MODE WIDGET OBJECT GRAPH — blessed applications
#      INSTANTIATE widget objects that live for the lifetime of the
#      app and are mutated in place:
#
#          const blessed = require('neo-blessed');
#          const screen = blessed.screen({smartCSR: true});
#          const box = blessed.box({
#              parent: screen,
#              top: 'center', left: 'center',
#              width: '50%', height: '50%',
#              content: 'Hello {bold}World{/bold}!',
#              tags: true,
#              border: {type: 'line'},
#              style: {fg: 'white', bg: 'magenta'}
#          });
#          screen.key(['q'], () => process.exit(0));
#          screen.render();
#
#      Compare ink R532 (React component tree with reconciler) and
#      ratatui R530 (immediate-mode widgets rebuilt each frame).
#      blessed is the RETAINED-MODE PARALLEL of tview R535 — both
#      use widget object graphs with mutable state.  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node retained-mode TUI library.
#
#   2. BUILT-IN WIDGET CATALOG (30+ widgets) — blessed ships with
#      one of the LARGEST built-in TUI widget catalogs in any
#      documented library:
#         * `Box`           — base widget with borders + padding
#         * `Text`           — static text with style tags
#         * `Line`           — horizontal/vertical separator line
#         * `ScrollableBox`  — auto-scrolling text container
#         * `ScrollableText` — text with built-in scrollbar
#         * `List`           — selectable list with arrow-key nav
#         * `Form`           — multi-input form container
#         * `Input`           — generic input widget (base)
#         * `Textarea`       — multi-line editable text
#         * `Textbox`        — single-line text input
#         * `Button`         — clickable button
#         * `ProgressBar`    — horizontal or vertical progress
#         * `FileManager`    — file picker with navigation
#         * `Checkbox`       — boolean toggle
#         * `RadioSet`       — radio button group
#         * `RadioButton`    — single radio
#         * `Prompt`         — modal prompt
#         * `Question`       — yes/no question modal
#         * `Message`        — modal alert
#         * `Loading`        — modal loading spinner
#         * `ListBar`        — horizontal list bar (like Vim's
#                              tabline)
#         * `Layout`         — auto-layout container
#         * `Image`          — ANSI-art image rendering
#         * `Terminal`       — embedded pty terminal (run a shell
#                              inside your TUI!)
#         * `Table`          — 2D data table
#         * `Log`            — auto-scrolling log viewer
#         * `Listtable`      — list with column alignment
#         * `Helpers`        — programmatic primitives
#         * `tput`           — terminfo capabilities exposure
#      Compare tview's ~16 built-ins (R535), bubbles' ~12 (R531),
#      ratatui's ~14 (R530), ink-core's ~5 (R532 plus ink-* packages).
#      blessed has the LARGEST built-in widget catalog of any
#      documented TUI library.
#
#   3. STYLE-TAG TEXT MARKUP — blessed's text content supports
#      INLINE STYLE TAGS:
#         `Hello {bold}World{/bold}, {red-fg}error{/red-fg}!`
#         `{center}centered{/center}`
#         `{|}right-aligned`
#         `{green-bg}{black-fg}status{/}`
#      Style tags work in any Text widget and are parsed at render
#      time.  Compare ratatui's `Span::styled()` constructor calls
#      (style is structural), bubbletea+lipgloss `lipgloss.NewStyle().
#      Foreground(lipgloss.Color("9")).Render(...)` (style is
#      programmatic), tview's `[red]error[white]` markup (similar
#      idea but different syntax).  blessed's tag syntax is the
#      MOST HTML-LIKE styling syntax in any documented TUI library.
#
#   4. MOUSE + KEYBOARD + RESIZE + FOCUS EVENT MODEL — blessed
#      handles ALL terminal events:
#         - Keyboard events (`screen.key([keys], handler)`)
#         - Mouse events (click, scroll, drag with `mouse: true`)
#         - Focus events (gained/lost, propagation)
#         - Resize events (terminal window resize)
#         - Tab navigation (Tab/Shift-Tab cycles focus)
#         - Custom event names (widget.on('selected', handler))
#      Compare ink R532's `useInput` hook (keyboard only without
#      explicit mouse/focus), tview's R535 `SetSelectedFunc` (also
#      callback-based).  blessed's event model is the most
#      COMPREHENSIVE of any documented TUI library — supports
#      drag-and-drop interactions that no other documented library
#      does.
#
#   5. SCREEN + ALTERNATE-BUFFER + TPUT-BASED RENDERING — blessed
#      renders by:
#         (a) Loading terminfo via `tput` capability strings
#         (b) Switching to alternate screen buffer (`smcup`)
#         (c) Maintaining a 2D `lines[y][x]` cell buffer
#         (d) Computing minimal diff between old and new buffers
#         (e) Emitting only the changed cells as ANSI/terminfo
#             escape sequences
#         (f) Restoring primary screen buffer on exit (`rmcup`)
#      This is the CANONICAL ncurses approach implemented entirely
#      in JavaScript.  Compare bubbletea (string-based diff),
#      ratatui (Buffer<Cell> diff via crossterm), tview (tcell-based
#      diff).  blessed is the FIRST documented TUI library that
#      explicitly uses terminfo + tput escape sequences for
#      cross-terminal portability.
#
# blessed's relationship to other documented TS-Node CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like `ink` R532 — full-screen TUI, takes over the terminal
#   * Like `chalk` R528 — uses ANSI escapes for color (but via
#                         terminfo, not hard-coded sequences)
#   * Like `ora` R524 — terminal-control-aware (raw mode + ANSI)
#   * Unlike ink R532 — RETAINED-MODE vs React-component-tree.
#                       blessed widgets are objects that LIVE;
#                       ink widgets are React components recomputed
#                       on every state change.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go:      `tview` R535 (retained-mode + tcell)
#         * Rust:    `cursive` (Gyscos/cursive, retained-mode,
#                     undocumented but ready for future round)
#     Adding cursive would complete the RETAINED-MODE TUI triple
#     across all top three languages.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE webpack-dashboard CLI — commander + neo-blessed Composition
#
# webpack-dashboard's argv parser is `tj/commander.js`:
#
#     const program = new commander.Command("webpack-dashboard")
#       .version(pkg.version)
#       .option("-c, --color [color]", "Dashboard color")
#       .option("-m, --minimal", "Minimal mode")
#       .option("-t, --title [title]", "Terminal window title")
#       .option("-p, --port [port]", "Socket listener port")
#       .option("-a, --include-assets [string prefix]",
#               "Asset names to limit to", collect, [])
#       .usage("[options] -- [script] [arguments]")
#       .parse(argv);
#
# Five flags + positional args after `--`.  The flags configure
# the blessed/neo-blessed TUI's color theme, layout density,
# terminal title, socket port, and asset filter.  Everything else
# happens in the blessed widget tree handling keyboard events and
# socket.io messages from the wrapped webpack process.
#
# Distinct from every other documented TS-Node CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. RETAINED-MODE WIDGET OBJECT GRAPH — Every other documented
#      TS-Node TUI library (ink R532) uses pure-React reconciler
#      rendering.  blessed uses RETAINED-MODE: widgets are persistent
#      objects mutated in place.  FIRST documented TS-Node retained-
#      mode TUI library.
#
#   2. 30+ BUILT-IN WIDGET CATALOG — Every other documented TS-Node
#      CLI library has 0-10 built-in widgets (chalk has 0, ora has
#      1 spinner widget, inquirer has ~8 prompt types, ink has ~5
#      primitives + community packages).  blessed has 30+ built-in
#      widgets including embedded-pty Terminal, FileManager,
#      ProgressBar, and Image.  FIRST documented TS-Node CLI
#      library with 30+ built-in widgets.
#
#   3. STYLE-TAG TEXT MARKUP — Every other documented TS-Node CLI
#      library uses programmatic styling (chalk's chain, ink's
#      <Text color=>) or no styling.  blessed uses INLINE STYLE
#      TAGS within text content (`{bold}word{/bold}`).  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node CLI library with HTML-like inline style
#      tag markup.
#
#   4. MOUSE + DRAG + FOCUS EVENT MODEL — Every other documented
#      TS-Node CLI library handles only keyboard events
#      (`useInput`, `inquirer prompt`, `ora keyboard interrupts`).
#      blessed handles mouse (click, scroll, drag), focus
#      (gained/lost/cycle), resize, and custom widget events.
#      FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library with mouse + drag +
#      focus event handling.
#
#   5. TERMINFO + TPUT-BASED RENDERING — Every other documented
#      TS-Node CLI library emits hard-coded ANSI escape sequences.
#      blessed reads the terminal's terminfo via `tput` and uses
#      the actual capability strings for the connected terminal.
#      FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library that uses terminfo
#      for cross-terminal portability.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/FormidableLabs/webpack-dashboard/blob/master/
# bin/webpack-dashboard.js commander definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '(-c --color)'{-c+,--color=}'[dashboard color theme]:color:(green blue red cyan magenta yellow white)' \
    '(-m --minimal)'{-m,--minimal}'[minimal layout mode]' \
    '(-t --title)'{-t+,--title=}'[terminal window title]:title:' \
    '(-p --port)'{-p+,--port=}'[socket.io listener port (default 9838)]:port:' \
    '*'{-a+,--include-assets=}'[asset-name prefix to display (repeatable)]:prefix:' \
    '*:webpack command and arguments after --:' \
    && ret=0

return ret
